{
  "doc_id": "41764",
  "text": "Local production of IL-18 has been reported to play an important role in driving the migration of dendritic cells to the kidney with attraction of more inflammatory cells and maintenance of kidney inflammation. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Data from several studies suggested that up-regulation of IL-18 in animal models and humans, is associated with nephritic kidneys and related to the degree of renal inflammation. [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] In our study, we found that serum levels of IL-18 showed significant increase among the different classes of glomerulonephritis, being higher in class IV and V LN than in class III and II LN. We have also demonstrated that serum IL-18 correlated significantly with the activity index of the renal biopsies.",
